# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acid-strength
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] In chemistry, the **Gutmann–Beckett method** is an experimental procedure used by chemists to assess the Lewis acidity of molecular species.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] Triethylphosphine oxide (Et3PO, TEPO) is used as a probe molecule and systems are evaluated by 31P-NMR spectroscopy.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] In 1975, Viktor Gutmann used 31P-NMR spectroscopy to parameterize Lewis acidity of solvents by **acceptor numbers** (AN).
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] Beckett recognised its more generally utility and adapted the procedure so that it could be easily applied to molecular species, when dissolved in weakly Lewis acidic solvents.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] The term *Gutmann–Beckett method* was first used in chemical literature in 2007.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] The 31P chemical shift (δ) of Et3PO is sensitive to chemical environment but can usually be found between +40 and +100 ppm.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] The O atom in Et3PO is a Lewis base, and its interaction with Lewis acid sites causes deshielding of the adjacent P atom.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] Acceptor numbers can be calculated from AN = 2.21 × (δsample − 41.0) and higher AN values indicate greater Lewis acidity.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] The Gutmann–Beckett method is based on a single parameter NMR chemical shift scale but is in commonly used due to its experimental convenience.
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] Boron trihalides are archetypal Lewis acids and have AN values between 89 (BF3) and 115 (BI3).
[src:acid-strength/acceptor-number] The Gutmann–Beckett method has been applied to fluoroarylboranes such as B(C6F5)3 (AN 82), and borenium cations, and its application to these and various other boron compounds has been reviewed.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] An **acetate** is a salt formed by the combination of acetic acid with a base (e.g. alkaline, earthy, metallic, nonmetallic, or radical base).
[src:acid-strength/acetate] "Acetate" also describes the conjugate base or ion (specifically, the negatively charged ion called an anion) typically found in aqueous solution and written with the chemical formula C 2H 3O− 2.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] The neutral molecules formed by the combination of the acetate ion and a *positive* ion (called a cation) are also commonly called "acetates" (hence, *acetate of lead*, *acetate of aluminium*, etc.).
[src:acid-strength/acetate] The simplest of these is hydrogen acetate (called acetic acid) with corresponding salts, esters, and the polyatomic anion CH 3CO− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Most of the approximately 5 million tonnes of acetic acid produced annually in industry are used in the production of acetates, which usually take the form of polymers.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] In nature, acetate is the most common building block for biosynthesis.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] When part of a salt, the formula of the acetate ion is written as CH 3CO− 2, C 2H 3O− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Chemists often represent acetate as OAc− or, less commonly, AcO−.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Thus, HOAc is the symbol for acetic acid, NaOAc for sodium acetate, and EtOAc for ethyl acetate (as Ac is common symbol for acetyl group CH3CO).
[src:acid-strength/acetate] The pseudoelement symbol "Ac" is also sometimes encountered in chemical formulas as indicating the entire acetate ion (CH 3CO− 2).
[src:acid-strength/acetate] It is not to be confused with the symbol of actinium, the first element of the actinide series; context guides disambiguation.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] For example, the formula for sodium acetate might be abbreviated as "NaOAc", rather than "NaC2H3O2".
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Care should also be taken to avoid confusion with peracetic acid when using the OAc abbreviation; for clarity and to avoid errors when translated, HOAc should be avoided in literature mentioning both compounds.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Although its systematic name is *ethanoate* (/ɪˈθænoʊ.eɪt/), the common *acetate* remains the preferred IUPAC name.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] The acetate anion, [CH3COO]−,(or [C2H3O2]−) is one of the carboxylate family.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] It is the conjugate base of acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Many acetate salts are ionic, indicated by their tendency to dissolve well in water.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Transition metals can be complexed by acetate.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Examples of acetate complexes include chromium(II) acetate and many other transition metal carboxylate complexes.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Commercially important acetate salts are aluminium acetate, used in dyeing, ammonium acetate, a precursor to acetamide, and potassium acetate, used as a diuretic.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] All three salts are colourless and highly soluble in water.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Acetate esters have the general formula CH3CO2R, where R is an organyl group.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] The esters are the dominant forms of acetate in the marketplace.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Unlike the acetate salts, acetate esters are often liquids, lipophilic, and sometimes volatile.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] They are popular because they have inoffensive, often sweet odors, they are inexpensive, and they are usually of low toxicity.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Almost half of acetic acid production is consumed in the production of vinyl acetate, precursor to polyvinyl alcohol, which is a component of many paints.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] The second largest use of acetic acid is consumed in the production of cellulose acetate.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] In fact, "acetate" is jargon for cellulose acetate, which is used in the production of fibres or diverse products, e.g. the acetate discs used in audio record production.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Cellulose acetate can be found in many household products.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Many industrial solvents are acetates, including methyl acetate, ethyl acetate, isopropyl acetate, and ethylhexyl acetate.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Butyl acetate is a fragrance used in food products.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] It is mainly utilized by organisms in the form of acetyl coenzyme A.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Intraperitoneal injection of sodium acetate (20 or 60 mg per kg body mass) was found to induce headache in sensitized rats, and it has been proposed that acetate resulting from oxidation of ethanol is a major factor in causing hangovers.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Increased serum acetate levels lead to accumulation of adenosine in many tissues including the brain, and administration of the adenosine receptor antagonist caffeine to rats after ethanol was found to decrease nociceptive behavior.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Acetate has known immunomodulatory properties and can affect the innate immune response to pathogenic bacteria such as the respiratory pathogen *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Pyruvate is converted into acetyl-coenzyme A (acetyl-CoA) by the enzyme pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] This acetyl-CoA is then converted into acetate in *E. coli*, whilst producing ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] Acetate formation requires two enzymes: phosphate acetyltransferase and acetate kinase.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] This disproportionation reaction is catalysed by methanogen archaea in their fermentative metabolism.
[src:acid-strength/acetate] One electron is transferred from the carbonyl function (e− donor) of the carboxylic group to the methyl group (e− acceptor) of acetic acid to respectively produce CO2 and methane gas.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:acid-strength/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:acid-strength/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] A weak acid is only partially dissociated, or is partly ionized in water with both the undissociated acid and its dissociation products being present, in solution, in equilibrium with each other.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Acetic acid (CH3COOH) is an example of a weak acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The strength of a weak acid is quantified by its acid dissociation constant, $K_{a}$ value.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The strength of a weak organic acid may depend on substituent effects.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The strength of an inorganic acid is dependent on the oxidation state for the atom to which the proton may be attached.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For example, hydrogen chloride is a strong acid in aqueous solution, but is a weak acid when dissolved in glacial acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The usual measure of the strength of an acid is its acid dissociation constant ( $K_{a}$ ), which can be determined experimentally by titration methods.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Stronger acids have a larger $K_{a}$ and a smaller logarithmic constant ( $\mathrm {p} K_{a}=-\log K_{a}$ ) than weaker acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H−A bond and the size of atom A, which determine the strength of the H−A bond.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Acid strengths also depend on the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Although these two concepts of acid strength often amount to the same general tendency of a substance to donate a proton, the $K_{a}$ and $H_{0}$ values are measures of distinct properties and may occasionally diverge.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For instance, hydrogen fluoride, whether dissolved in water ( $\mathrm {p} K_{a}=3.2$ ) or DMSO ( $\mathrm {p} K_{a}=15$ ), has $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ values indicating that it undergoes incomplete dissociation in these solvents, making it a weak acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] However, as the rigorously dried, neat acidic medium, hydrogen fluoride has an $H_{0}$ value of –15, making it a more strongly protonating medium than 100% sulfuric acid and thus, by definition, a superacid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] (To prevent ambiguity, in the rest of this article, "strong acid" will, unless otherwise stated, refer to an acid that is strong as measured by its $\mathrm {p} K_{{\ce {a}}}$ value ( $\mathrm {p} K_{{\ce {a}}}<-1.74$ ).
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] When the acidic medium in question is a dilute aqueous solution, the $H_{0}$ is approximately equal to the pH value, which is a negative logarithm of the concentration of aqueous H+ in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The pH of a simple solution of an acid in water is determined by both $K_{a}$ and the acid concentration.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For weak acid solutions, it depends on the degree of dissociation, which may be determined by an equilibrium calculation.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For concentrated solutions of acids, especially strong acids for which pH < 0, the $H_{0}$ value is a better measure of acidity than the pH.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] where S represents a solvent molecule, such as a molecule of water or dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), to such an extent that the concentration of the undissociated species HA is too low to be measured.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For practical purposes a strong acid can be said to be completely dissociated.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] An example of a strong acid is perchloric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Any acid with a $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ value which is less than about −2 behaves as a strong acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] This results from the very high buffer capacity of solutions with a pH value of 1 or less and is known as the leveling effect.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The following are strong acids in aqueous and dimethyl sulfoxide solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] As mentioned above, because the dissociation is so strongly favored, the concentrations of HA and thus the values of $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ cannot be measured experimentally.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The values in the following table are average values from as many as 8 different theoretical calculations.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Sulfonic acids, such as *p*-toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid) are a class of strong organic oxyacids.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Some sulfonic acids can be isolated as solids.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is an example of a substance that is a solid strong acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] A weak acid is a substance that partially dissociates or partly ionizes when it is dissolved in a solvent.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] In solution, there is an equilibrium between the acid, HA, and the products of dissociation.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The solvent (e.g. water) is omitted from this expression when its concentration is effectively unchanged by the process of acid dissociation.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Typical examples of weak acids include acetic acid and phosphorous acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] An acid such as oxalic acid (HOOC−COOH) is said to be dibasic because it can lose two protons and react with two molecules of a simple base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For a more rigorous treatment of acid strength see acid dissociation constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] This includes acids such as the dibasic acid succinic acid, for which the simple method of calculating the pH of a solution, shown above, cannot be used.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The experimental determination of a $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ value is commonly performed by means of a titration.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] A quantity of strong acid is added to a solution containing the acid or a salt of the acid, to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] until only the deprotonated species, A−, remains in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The equilibrium constant is found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] It is sometimes stated that "the conjugate of a weak acid is a strong base".
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For example, acetic acid is a weak acid which has a $K_{a}=1.75\times 10^{-5}$ .
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Its conjugate base is the acetate ion with $K_{b}=10^{-14}$ and $K_{a}=5.7\times 10^{-10}$ (from the relationship $K_{a}\times K_{b}=10^{-14}$ ), which certainly does not correspond to a strong base.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The conjugate of a weak acid is often a weak base and vice versa.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The strength of an acid varies from solvent to solvent.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] An acid which is strong in water may be weak in a less basic solvent, and an acid which is weak in water may be strong in a more basic solvent.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] According to Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory, the solvent S can accept a proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For example, hydrochloric acid is a weak acid in solution in pure acetic acid, HO2CCH3, which is less basic than water.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The extent of ionization of the hydrohalic acids decreases in the order HI > HBr > HCl.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Acetic acid is said to be a differentiating solvent for the three acids, while water is not.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] An important example of a solvent which is more basic than water is dimethyl sulfoxide, DMSO, (CH3)2SO.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] A compound which is a weak acid in water may become a strong acid in DMSO.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Acetic acid is an example of such a substance.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] An extensive bibliography of $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ values in solution in DMSO and other solvents can be found at Acidity–Basicity Data in Nonaqueous Solvents.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Superacids are strong acids even in solvents of low dielectric constant.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid and magic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] Lewis acids reacting with Lewis bases in gas phase and non-aqueous solvents have been classified in the ECW model, and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] For the qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for the quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] In organic carboxylic acids, an electronegative substituent can pull electron density out of an acidic bond through the inductive effect, resulting in a smaller $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ value.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The effect decreases, the further the electronegative element is from the carboxylate group, as illustrated by the following series of halogenated butanoic acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] In a set of oxoacids of an element, $\mathrm {p} K_{a}$ values decrease with the oxidation state of the element.
[src:acid-strength/acid-strength] The oxoacids of chlorine illustrate this trend.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:acid-strength/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:acid-strength/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:acid-strength/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:acid-strength/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:acid-strength/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:acid-strength/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:acid-strength/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:acid-strength/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:acid-strength/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:acid-strength/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:acid-strength/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:acid-strength/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:acid-strength/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:acid-strength/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:acid-strength/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:acid-strength/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:acid-strength/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:acid-strength/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:acid-strength/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:acid-strength/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:acid-strength/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:acid-strength/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:acid-strength/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:acid-strength/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:acid-strength/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:acid-strength/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:acid-strength/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:acid-strength/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:acid-strength/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:acid-strength/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:acid-strength/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:acid-strength/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:acid-strength/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:acid-strength/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:acid-strength/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:acid-strength/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:acid-strength/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] An **acidic oxide** is an oxide that either produces an acidic solution upon addition to water, or acts as an acceptor of hydroxide ions effectively functioning as a Lewis acid.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Acidic oxides will typically have a low pKa and may be inorganic or organic.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] A commonly encountered acidic oxide, carbon dioxide produces an acidic solution (and the generation of carbonic acid) when dissolved.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Generally non-metallic oxides are acidic.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] The acidity of an oxide can be reasonably assumed by its accompanying constituents.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Less electronegative elements tend to form basic oxides such as sodium oxide and magnesium oxide, whereas more electronegative elements tend to produce acidic oxides such as carbon dioxide and phosphorus pentoxide.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Some oxides, like aluminium oxides, are amphoteric, while some oxides may be neutral.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Acidic oxides are of environmental concern.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Sulfur and nitrogen oxides are considered air pollutants as they react with atmospheric water vapour to produce acid rain.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Carbonic acid is an illustrative example of the Lewis acidity of an acidic oxide.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] This property is a key reason for keeping alkali chemicals well sealed from the atmosphere, as long-term exposure to carbon dioxide in the air can degrade the material.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] Aluminium oxide (Al2O3) is an amphoteric oxide; it can act as a base or acid.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] It will react with strong bases to form silicate salts.
[src:acid-strength/acidic-oxide] This reaction is important in the manufacturing of sulfuric acid.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] An **acidity function** is a measure of the acidity of a medium or solvent system, usually expressed in terms of its ability to donate protons to (or accept protons from) a solute (Brønsted acidity).
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] The pH scale is by far the most commonly used acidity function, and is ideal for dilute aqueous solutions.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] Other acidity functions have been proposed for different environments, most notably the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] The term acidity function is also used for measurements made on basic systems, and the term **basicity function** is uncommon.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] where p*K*a is the dissociation constant of BH+.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] They were originally measured by using nitroanilines as weak bases or acid-base indicators and by measuring the concentrations of the protonated and unprotonated forms with UV-visible spectroscopy.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] Other spectroscopic methods, such as NMR, may also be used.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] Here BH is a weak acid used as an acid-base indicator, and B− is its conjugate base.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] In dilute aqueous solution, the predominant acid species is the hydrated hydrogen ion H3O+ (or more accurately [H(OH2)n]+).
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] In this case *H*0 and *H*− are equivalent to pH values determined by the buffer equation or Henderson-Hasselbalch equation.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] However, an *H*0 value of −21 (a 25% solution of SbF5 in HSO3F) does not imply a hydrogen ion concentration of 1021 mol/dm3: such a "solution" would have a density more than a hundred times greater than a neutron star.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] Rather, *H*0 = −21 implies that the reactivity (protonating power) of the solvated hydrogen ions is 1021 times greater than the reactivity of the hydrated hydrogen ions in an aqueous solution of pH 0.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] The actual reactive species are different in the two cases, but both can be considered to be sources of H+, i.e.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] The hydrogen ion H+ *never* exists on its own in a condensed phase, as it is always solvated to a certain extent.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] The high negative value of *H*0 in SbF5/HSO3F mixtures indicates that the solvation of the hydrogen ion is much weaker in this solvent system than in water.
[src:acid-strength/acidity-function] Other way of expressing the same phenomenon is to say that SbF5·FSO3H is a much stronger proton donor than H3O+.
